Nigerian Breweries Plc is raising up to N48 billion in the seven and eight series of its commercial paper (CP) programme to support its short-term funding. The company in a release to the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) and the investing public capital market community of the continuation of its Commercial Paper, signed by the company secretary/legal director, Uaboi Agbebaku, said the launch of Series seven and eight of the programme  opened yesterday April 6, 2020, saying that while Series seven would be for a tenor of 182 days, Series eight would be for 270 days. According to Nigerian Breweries, the CP programme aims to raise up to a maximum of N48 billion to support the Company’s short term funding needs. “The CP Programme continues to provide the opportunity for non-equity investors to invest in the Company, support the Company’s cost management initiatives and serve as an additional source of funding for the Company.” Commercial paper is a money-market security issued or sold by large corporations to obtain funds to meet short-term debt obligations and is backed only by an issuing bank or company promise to pay the face amount on the maturity date specified on the note. The Company for the financial year ended December 31, 2019 declared a final dividend recommendation of N16.07 billion for its shareholders. The dividend which is subject to shareholders’ approval  at the Company forthcoming Annual General Meeting scheduled for April 22, 2020.  The recommendation is coming on the heels of the N16.1 billion profit after tax recorded by the company in 2019, signifying a 100 per cent earnings-payout ratio. The N16.07 billion total dividend amounts to N2.01 per share for the 2019 operating year. The had earlier paid an interim dividend of N3.9 billion, that is 50 kobo, totalling final dividend of N12.07 billion that is, N1.51 per share to be received by the shareholders for 2019 financial year. In a statement also signed by Agbebaku, the Board announced a N16.1 billion profit after tax for 2019 on a revenue of  N323 billion. The amount represents a 0.4 per cent decrease in revenue from the N324 billion earned in 2018. The statement also shows that profit before tax dropped to N23.3 billion in 2019 from N29.4 billion in the previous year, indicating a 20.5 per cent fall. According to the statement, in 2019, the results of the Company was adversely impacted by the second instalment of the increased excise duty rates which came into effect during the year coupled with a challenging operating environment. In order to mitigate the cost pressure due to government hike in excise duty rates in 2018, the company in April 2019, launched its second N100 billion Commercial Papers (CPs) programme, aimed at reducing its funding cost and support short term funding needs. Four series were successfully issued in 2019 with total amount raised put at N30 billion. The series five and six were launched on the February 3, 2020 with a plan to raise N45 billion. 